Below is a very detailed, easy-to-understand introduction of MySQL focused ONLY on:
	1. Constraints (Conditions)
	2. Data Types
	3. Examples using Indian names
The explanation is written in simple language, exam-oriented, and is long enough to cover about 5 handwritten pages (or ~4–5 A4 pages).
You can directly use this for records, assignments, or theory exams.

**INTRODUCTION TO MySQL
(Constraints and Data Types)**
1. Introduction to MySQL
MySQL is an open-source Relational Database Management System (RDBMS) used to store, manage, and retrieve data in an organized manner.
It uses SQL (Structured Query Language) to interact with the database.
In MySQL, data is stored in the form of tables, which contain rows and columns.
Each column has a data type, and each table can have constraints to control the data.
To maintain data accuracy, consistency, and integrity, MySQL provides:
	• Data Types → define what kind of data can be stored
	• Constraints → define rules or conditions on data

2. What are Data Types in MySQL?
A data type specifies the type of value that a column can store.
For example:
	• Name → text
	• Age → number
	• Date of Birth → date
Using correct data types helps to:
	• Save storage space
	• Improve performance
	• Avoid invalid data entry

3. Categories of Data Types in MySQL
MySQL data types are mainly divided into:
	1. Numeric Data Types
	2. String (Character) Data Types
	3. Date and Time Data Types

4. Numeric Data Types (With Indian Examples)
Numeric data types are used to store numbers.
4.1 INT
	• Used to store whole numbers
	• Example: roll number, age, marks
age INT
Example Table:
CREATE TABLE student_age (
    student_id INT,
    name VARCHAR(50),
    age INT
);
Sample Data:
	• Rahul – 18
	• Anjali – 17
	• Suresh – 19

4.2 BIGINT
	• Used to store very large numbers
	• Example: Aadhaar number, large ID numbers
aadhaar_number BIGINT
Example:
CREATE TABLE citizens (
    name VARCHAR(50),
    aadhaar_number BIGINT
);
Example data:
	• Ramesh – 987654321012
	• Sunita – 912345678901

4.3 DECIMAL
	• Used to store exact decimal values
	• Example: fees, salary, marks with decimal
fees DECIMAL(8,2)
Example:
CREATE TABLE fees_details (
    student_name VARCHAR(50),
    fees DECIMAL(8,2)
);
Example:
	• Mahesh – 4500.50
	• Priya – 3800.00

5. String (Character) Data Types
String data types are used to store text.

5.1 CHAR
	• Fixed-length string
	• Used when data length is always same
gender CHAR(1)
Example:
	• M
	• F

5.2 VARCHAR
	• Variable-length string
	• Most commonly used
name VARCHAR(50)
Example Table:
CREATE TABLE students (
    student_id INT,
    name VARCHAR(50),
    city VARCHAR(30)
);
Example data:
	• Akash – Bengaluru
	• Neha – Mumbai
	• Rohan – Pune

5.3 TEXT
	• Used to store large text
	• Example: address, description
address TEXT
Example:
CREATE TABLE employee (
    name VARCHAR(50),
    address TEXT
);
Example:
	• Shyam – “Near MG Road, Bengaluru, Karnataka”

6. Date and Time Data Types
These data types are used to store dates and time.

6.1 DATE
	• Stores date in YYYY-MM-DD format
dob DATE
Example:
CREATE TABLE student_dob (
    name VARCHAR(50),
    dob DATE
);
Example:
	• Kavya – 2006-05-12
	• Arjun – 2005-11-20

6.2 TIME
	• Stores time
login_time TIME
Example:
	• 09:30:00
	• 14:45:10

6.3 DATETIME
	• Stores both date and time
created_at DATETIME
Example:
CREATE TABLE login_details (
    username VARCHAR(50),
    login_time DATETIME
);
Example:
	• Ritu – 2025-01-10 09:15:00

7. What are Constraints in MySQL?
Constraints are rules or conditions applied to columns to restrict the type of data that can be stored.
Constraints help to:
	• Prevent invalid data
	• Maintain data accuracy
	• Maintain data integrity

8. Types of Constraints in MySQL
Common constraints are:
	1. NOT NULL
	2. UNIQUE
	3. PRIMARY KEY
	4. FOREIGN KEY
	5. CHECK
	6. DEFAULT

9. NOT NULL Constraint
	• Ensures a column cannot have empty values
name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL
Example:
CREATE TABLE students (
    student_id INT,
    name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL
);
 Invalid:
	• name = NULL
Valid:
	• name = “Sanjay”

10. UNIQUE Constraint
	• Ensures no duplicate values
email VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE
Example:
CREATE TABLE users (
    username VARCHAR(50),
    email VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE
);
Example:
	• Amit@gmail.com 
	• Amit@gmail.com  (duplicate)

11. PRIMARY KEY Constraint
	• Combines NOT NULL + UNIQUE
	• Identifies each record uniquely
student_id INT PRIMARY KEY
Example:
CREATE TABLE students (
    student_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(50)
);
Example:
	• student_id = 101 
	• student_id = 101  (duplicate)

12. FOREIGN KEY Constraint
	• Links one table to another
	• Maintains relationship between tables
class_id INT,
FOREIGN KEY (class_id) REFERENCES classes(class_id)
Example:
CREATE TABLE students (
    student_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(50),
    class_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (class_id) REFERENCES classes(class_id)
);
Example:
	• Rohit → Class 10 
	• Rohit → Class 15  (not exists)

13. CHECK Constraint
	• Applies a condition on values
CHECK (age >= 5)
Example:
CREATE TABLE students (
    name VARCHAR(50),
    age INT CHECK (age >= 5)
);
Example:
	• Age = 10 
	• Age = 3 

14. DEFAULT Constraint
	• Assigns a default value if none is provided
city VARCHAR(30) DEFAULT 'Bengaluru'
Example:
CREATE TABLE employees (
    name VARCHAR(50),
    city VARCHAR(30) DEFAULT 'Mumbai'
);
Example:
	• If city not entered → Mumbai automatically stored

15. Importance of Data Types and Constraints
Using correct data types and constraints:
	• Prevents wrong data entry
	• Improves database performance
	• Ensures data reliability
	• Makes database professional and secure

16. Conclusion
MySQL data types define what kind of data can be stored, while constraints define rules on that data.
Together, they ensure accuracy, consistency, and integrity of the database.
Understanding data types and constraints is very important for:
	• DBMS exams
	• Mini projects
	• Real-world applications

One-Line Exam Conclusion:
	“In MySQL, data types specify the type of data stored in columns, and constraints apply conditions to maintain data accuracy and integrity.”
